              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18418108584669137917">Elizabeth Kostova writes very slowly, very few books. Much to my dismay. Luckily, the books are really long, so I get to spend some serious time with them. <br/><br/>I guess Kostova’s style could be called slow-burn. The tension builds with agonizing gradualness. I love it! I’m thinking, “this is a little slow....” then, suddenly, I’m completely immersed. <br/><br/>This particular story is about art, artists, a psychologist, and a mysterious crime. Which, like the best stories, involves a mysterious woman. And a do</span>
  <span id="freeText18418108584669137917" style="display:none">Elizabeth Kostova writes very slowly, very few books. Much to my dismay. Luckily, the books are really long, so I get to spend some serious time with them. <br /><br />I guess Kostova’s style could be called slow-burn. The tension builds with agonizing gradualness. I love it! I’m thinking, “this is a little slow....” then, suddenly, I’m completely immersed. <br /><br />This particular story is about art, artists, a psychologist, and a mysterious crime. Which, like the best stories, involves a mysterious woman. And a doctor who plays a detective. And crosses some lines. Is he confusing his life with his patient’s?<br /><br />So good! Her books enthrall me. Smart and deep.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18418108584669137917" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

